{"title_page": "Millais School", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox school \n| name          = Millais School\n| image         = Millais School, Horsham.jpg\n| image_size          = 200px\n| coordinates   = {{coord|51.06377|-0.30732|type:edu_region:GB_dim:100|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| motto         = \n| established   = \n| closed        = \n| type          = [[Community school (England and Wales)|Community school]]\n| religious_affiliation      = \n| president     = \n| head_label    = Headteacher\n| head          = Dr Alison Lodwick\n| r_head_label  = \n| r_head        = \n| chair_label   = \n| chair         =\n| founder       = \n| address        = Depot Road\n| city          = [[Horsham]]\n| county        = [[West Sussex]]\n| country       = [[England]]\n| postcode      = RH13 5HR\n| local_authority           = [[West Sussex County Council|West Sussex]]\n| ofsted        = yes\n| dfeno         = 938/4010\n| urn           = 126066\n| staff         =\n| enrolment    = 1,550\n| gender        = Girls\n| lower_age     = 11\n| upper_age     = 16\n| houses        = \n| colours       = Green, black and white\n| publication   = \n| free_label_1  = \n| free_1        = \n| free_label_2  = \n| free_2        = \n| free_label_3  = \n| free_3        = \n| website       = http://www.millais.org.uk/\n}}\n\n'''Millais School''' is a  girls' secondary school for students aged 11\u201316 situated in Horsham, West Sussex, England. There is no sixth form and the number on roll is over 1500 and rising due to the school's popularity. In July 2011 the school was approached by the government and became a National Teaching School. \nThe school's catchment area serves Horsham and the villages bordering the town. The Headteacher is Dr. Alison Lodwick, and the two Deputy Heads are Mrs S. Springer and Mr. M. Sutton. Elizabeth Barnes is the Chairman of Governors.\n\n== Reputation ==\nMillais achieved Outstanding OFSTED inspections in March 2010 and again in May 2014 with every area (Achievement of pupils, Quality of teaching, Behaviour and safety of pupils, Leadership and management) being classified as Outstanding (the highest category).{{Citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n\nAlthough exam results are consistently exceptional, a unique aspect of the school is its language provision with students studying a wide range including Chinese, French, German, Italian and Spanish. The exchange programme offered includes many visits abroad and the China visit, which has run for over a decade, includes visits to Beijing, Shanghai and Xian, home of the Terracotta Warriors.\n \nMillais students also go on to attend the best universities in the world. This varies each year, but annually several students (sometimes double figures) reach Oxford and Cambridge, with others choosing the Ivy League, including Harvard in the United States. Millais girls also pursue excellence beyond the academic arena and the school has an exceptional reputation for sport with many girls representing Sussex and several representing England in international competitions. Students also perform in the West End and Chichester Playhouse Theatre and there is a thriving alumni of almost a thousand former students, many of whom return to Millais to talk to current students about their experiences and give tips and advice.\n\n== History ==\nThe school's history can be traced back to 1928, when the Oxford Road Senior School opened. This was a co-educational school that in 1932 had an average attendance of 208: 116 boys and 92 girls; by 1938, this number had risen to 294: 153 boys and 141 girls. After 1944, the school split into Horsham secondary boys' and girls' schools.\n\nAs Horsham Secondary School for Girls in 1951, it received pupils from Broadbridge Heath, Slinfold, Southwater, and Colgate. In 1958, it moved to its current location on Depot Road, around the corner from the site of the Boys' school, which had moved to Comptons Lane four years previously. Both schools were renamed The Forest School, and the boys' school still retains this name.\n\nIn 1976, the school became a comprehensive, and the following year was renamed The Millais School. In 1980, there were 1,097 girls on roll.<ref>[http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=18358 Horsham - Education | British History Online<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nIn September 1996, the school was designated a language college and currently teaches five languages: French, Spanish, German, Italian and Chinese. Students are taught French and one other language for their initial three years and must then continue at least one as a full course GCSE in their final two years at the school (though many also continue a second language as either a shortcourse, accelerated or full course GCSE).\n\nMillais has been a training school since 2006; the school operates the Millais Alliance to this end.<ref>[http://www.millaisalliance.org.uk/ The Millais Alliance], Millais School.</ref>\n\nThe school's success has been based on constant innovation whilst building on existing strengths. In the last twenty years there have been only two Headteachers, Mr Leon Nettley and current Headteacher Dr. Alison Lodwick.\n\nThe school is named after [[John Everett Millais]], and his [[monogram]], J E M, is incorporated into the school's logo.\n\nIn 2014, the school experienced a deliberately set fire that badly damaged the third floor of a building. The fire was treated as criminal in nature, and a  16 year old girl was subsequently arrested and charged with arson and intent to endanger life.<ref>{{cite web |title=School fire investigated as crime |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-sussex-26696854 |website=BBC |accessdate=19 May 2019 |date=22 March 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Girl, 16, charged over school fire |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-sussex-26730787 |website=BBC |accessdate=19 May 2019 |date=25 March 2014}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* http://www.millais.org.uk/ - the school's website\n\n{{Schools in West Sussex}}\n\n[[Category:Secondary schools in West Sussex]]\n[[Category:Girls' schools in West Sussex]]\n[[Category:Community schools in West Sussex]]\n[[Category:Training schools in England]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox school \n| name          = Millais School\n| image         = Millais School, Horsham.jpg\n| image_size          = 200px\n| coordinates   = {{coord|51.06377|-0.30732|type:edu_region:GB_dim:100|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| motto         = \n| established   = \n| closed        = \n| type          = [[Community school (England and Wales)|Community school]]\n| religious_affiliation      = \n| president     = \n| head_label    = Headteacher\n| head          = Dr Alison Lodwick\n| r_head_label  = \n| r_head        = \n| chair_label   = \n| chair         =\n| founder       = \n| address        = Depot Road\n| city          = [[Horsham]]\n| county        = [[West Sussex]]\n| country       = [[England]]\n| postcode      = RH13 5HR\n| local_authority           = [[West Sussex County Council|West Sussex]]\n| ofsted        = yes\n| dfeno         = 938/4010\n| urn           = 126066\n| staff         =\n| enrolment    = 1,550\n| gender        = Girls\n| lower_age     = 11\n| upper_age     = 16\n| houses        = \n| colours       = Green, black and white\n| publication   = \n| free_label_1  = \n| free_1        = \n| free_label_2  = \n| free_2        = \n| free_label_3  = \n| free_3        = \n| website       = http://www.millais.org.uk/\n}}\n\n'''Millais School''' is a  girls' secondary school for students aged 11\u201316 situated in Horsham, West Sussex, England. There is no sixth form and the number on roll is over 1500 and rising due to the school's popularity. In July 2011 the school was approached by the government and became a National Teaching School. \nThe school's catchment area serves Horsham and the villages bordering the town. The Headteacher is Dr. Alison Lodwick, and the two Deputy Heads are Mrs S. Springer and Mr. M. Sutton. Elizabeth Barnes is the Chairman of Governors.\n\n== Reputation ==\nMillais achieved Outstanding OFSTED inspections in March 2010 and again in May 2014 with every area (Achievement of pupils, Quality of teaching, Behaviour and safety of pupils, Leadership and management) being classified as Outstanding (the highest category).{{Citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n\nAlthough exam results are consistently exceptional, a unique aspect of the school is its language provision with students studying a wide range including Chinese, French, German, Italian, Latin and Spanish. The exchange programme offered includes many visits abroad and the China visit, which has run for over a decade, includes visits to Beijing, Shanghai and Xian, home of the Terracotta Warriors.\n \nMillais students also go on to attend the best universities in the world. This varies each year, but annually several students (sometimes double figures) reach Oxford and Cambridge, with others choosing the Ivy League, including Harvard in the United States. Millais girls also pursue excellence beyond the academic arena and the school has an exceptional reputation for sport with many girls representing Sussex and several representing England in international competitions. Students also perform in the West End and Chichester Playhouse Theatre and there is a thriving alumni of almost a thousand former students, many of whom return to Millais to talk to current students about their experiences and give tips and advice.\n\n== History ==\nThe school's history can be traced back to 1928, when the Oxford Road Senior School opened. This was a co-educational school that in 1932 had an average attendance of 208: 116 boys and 92 girls; by 1938, this number had risen to 294: 153 boys and 141 girls. After 1944, the school split into Horsham secondary boys' and girls' schools.\n\nAs Horsham Secondary School for Girls in 1951, it received pupils from Broadbridge Heath, Slinfold, Southwater, and Colgate. In 1958, it moved to its current location on Depot Road, around the corner from the site of the Boys' school, which had moved to Comptons Lane four years previously. Both schools were renamed The Forest School, and the boys' school still retains this name.\n\nIn 1976, the school became a comprehensive, and the following year was renamed The Millais School. In 1980, there were 1,097 girls on roll.<ref>[http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=18358 Horsham - Education | British History Online<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nIn September 1996, the school was designated a language college and currently teaches five languages: French, Spanish, German, Italian and Chinese. Students are taught French and one other language for their initial three years and must then continue at least one as a full course GCSE in their final two years at the school (though many also continue a second language as either a shortcourse, accelerated or full course GCSE).\n\nMillais has been a training school since 2006; the school operates the Millais Alliance to this end.<ref>[http://www.millaisalliance.org.uk/ The Millais Alliance], Millais School.</ref>\n\nThe school's success has been based on constant innovation whilst building on existing strengths. In the last twenty years there have been only two Headteachers, Mr Leon Nettley and current Headteacher Dr. Alison Lodwick.\n\nThe school is named after [[John Everett Millais]], and his [[monogram]], J E M, is incorporated into the school's logo.\n\nIn 2014, the school experienced a deliberately set fire that badly damaged the third floor of a building. The fire was treated as criminal in nature, and a  16 year old girl was subsequently arrested and charged with arson and intent to endanger life.<ref>{{cite web |title=School fire investigated as crime |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-sussex-26696854 |website=BBC |accessdate=19 May 2019 |date=22 March 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Girl, 16, charged over school fire |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-sussex-26730787 |website=BBC |accessdate=19 May 2019 |date=25 March 2014}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* http://www.millais.org.uk/ - the school's website\n\n{{Schools in West Sussex}}\n\n[[Category:Secondary schools in West Sussex]]\n[[Category:Girls' schools in West Sussex]]\n[[Category:Community schools in West Sussex]]\n[[Category:Training schools in England]]\n", "name_user": "Brianthekoolguy", "label": "safe", "comment": "They no longer provide Latin language, so it was removed from the list of languagues", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Millais_School"}
{"title_page": "Robert B. Parker", "text_new": "{{short description|American crime writer}}\n{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| name = Robert B. Parker\n| image = Robert_B._Parker_at_Manchester_Library.jpg\n| imagesize =\n| caption = Parker Robertsonss in 2053\n| pseudonym = he is a banana\n| birth_name = Robert Brown Parker\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1932|9|17}}\n| birth_place = [[Springfield, Massachusetts]], [[U.S.]]\n| death_date = {{death date and age|2010|1|18|1932|9|17}}<ref name=\"AP death notice\">{{cite news|url=http://www.bostonherald.com/entertainment/books/view.bg?articleid=1226710&pos=breaking |title='Spenser' novelist Robert Parker dies in Cambridge |agency=[[Associated Press]] |work=[[Boston Herald]] |date=2010-01-19 |accessdate=2010-01-19}}</ref>\n| death_place = [[Cambridge, Massachusetts]], [[U.S.]]\n| occupation = Novelist\n| period = 1974\u20132010\n| genre = [[Crime fiction|Detective fiction]], [[Western fiction]]\n| subject =\n| movement =\n| spouse = Joan Hall Parker (1956 \u20132010)\n| partner =\n| children = 2 sons\n| relatives =\n| signature =\n| website = {{URL|robertbparker.net}}\n}}\n'''Robert Brown Parker''' (September 17, 1932 &ndash; January 18, 2010) was an American writer of fiction, primarily of the mystery/detective genre.  His most famous works were the 40 novels written about the fictional  [[private detective]] [[Spenser (character)|Spenser]]. [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] television network developed the television series ''[[Spenser: For Hire]]'' based on the character in the mid-1980s; a [[Spenser (TV movies)|series of TV movies]] based on the character was also produced. His works incorporate encyclopedic knowledge of the [[Boston]] metropolitan area.<ref>{{cite book  | last = Geherin  | first = David  | title = Sons of Sam Spade: the private-eye novel in the 70s: Robert B. Parker, Roger L. Simon, Andrew Bergman  | publisher = Ungar  | year = c. 1980  | isbn = 0-8044-2231-1 }}</ref> The Spenser novels have been cited by critics and bestselling authors such as [[Robert Crais]], [[Harlan Coben]], and [[Dennis Lehane]]<ref>\"His Spenser Novels Saved Detective Fiction\" by Tom Nolan, ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'' [https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748703837004575013104258735756]</ref> as not only influencing their own work but reviving and changing the detective genre.<ref>\"Robert B. Parker left a mark on the detective novel\" by Sarah Weinman, ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' [http://articles.latimes.com/2010/jan/20/entertainment/la-et-robert-parker20-2010jan20]</ref>  \n\nParker also wrote two other series based on an individual character:  He wrote nine novels based on the fictional character [[Jesse Stone (character)|Jesse Stone]], a Los Angeles police officer who moves to a small New England town, and six novels based on the fictional character Sunny Randall, a female private investigator. Parker wrote four Westerns starring the duo Virgil Cole and Everett Hitch. The first, ''[[Appaloosa (novel)|Appaloosa]]'', was made into a film starring [[Ed Harris]].\n\n==Early life==\nParker was born in [[Springfield, Massachusetts]].<ref name=\"litweb\">[http://www.litweb.net/biogs/parker_robert_b.html Robert B. Parker biography] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100211045212/http://litweb.net/biogs/parker_robert_b.html |date=2010-02-11 }} from Litweb.net</ref> In 1956 Parker married Joan H. Parker, whom he claimed to have met as a toddler at a birthday party.<ref name=\"Times obit\">{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/01/20/books/20parker.html | title=Robert B. Parker, the Prolific Writer Who Created Spenser, Is Dead at 77 | author= Bruce Weber | date= January 20, 2010 | work= [[The New York Times]] | accessdate = January 20, 2010}}</ref> They spent their childhoods in the same neighborhood.<ref>{{cite web|author=Jules Older |url=http://www.yankeemagazine.com/issues/2003-10/robert-parker |title=Robert B. Parker 2003 Interview |work=Yankee Magazine |date=October 2003 |accessdate=2010-02-23}}</ref>\n\nAfter earning a BA degree from [[Colby College]] in [[Waterville, Maine]], Parker served as a soldier in the [[United States Army|US Army]] Infantry in [[Korea]].  In 1957, he earned his master's degree in [[English literature]] from [[Boston University]] and then worked in advertising and technical writing until 1962.<ref name=\"litweb\" /> Parker received a PhD in English literature from Boston University in 1971.<ref name=\"reporter\">[http://www.bookreporter.com/authors/au-parker-robert.asp Author Profile: Robert B. Parker] from BookReporter.com</ref>  His dissertation, titled \"The Violent Hero, Wilderness Heritage and Urban Reality,\" discussed the exploits of fictional private-eye heroes created by [[Dashiell Hammett]], [[Raymond Chandler]], and [[Ross Macdonald]].<ref name=\"litweb\" />\n\n==Career==\nParker wrote his first novel<ref name=\"reporter\" /> in 1971 while teaching at [[Northeastern University]].<!--The article without the disambiguation is about the school in Boston.--> He became a full professor in 1976, and turned to full-time writing in 1979 with five Spenser novels to his credit.<ref name=\"litweb\" />\n\nParker's popular [[Spenser (character)|Spenser]] novels are known for his characters of varied races and religions.  According to critic Christina Nunez, Parker's \"inclusion of [characters of] other races and sexual persuasions\" lends his writings a \"more modern feel\".<ref>{{cite web| author=Christina Nunez |url=http://www.barnesandnoble.com/writers/writerdetails.asp?cid=802368 |title=Robert B. Parker Biography |work=Barnes and Noble |accessdate=2010-02-23}}</ref>  For example, the ''Spenser'' series characters include Hawk and Chollo, African-American and Mexican-American, respectively, as well as Spenser's Jewish girlfriend, Susan, various Russians, Ukrainians, Chinese, a gay cop, Lee Farrell, and even a gay mob boss, Gino Fish.<ref>See nearly the entire Spenser series for Hawk, whose prominence in the plots increases with each book; for Chollo, ''Stardust'', ''[[Pot Shot]]'', and ''Now and Then''; ''[[Cold Service]]'' features Ukrainian and Russian mobsters; and ''[[Walking Shadow]]'', which explores [[Tong (organization)|Chinese tongs]] and includes a Chinese-American translator named Mei Ling who has a relationship with Hawk; see ''[[Chance (Parker novel)|Chance]]'' for Gino Fish, who also crosses over into the first Jesse Stone novel.</ref> The homosexuality of both his sons gave his writing \"[a] sensibility,\" Ms. Nunez feels, \"[which] strengthens Parker's sensibility [toward gays].\"  In 1985 ''Spenser'' was made into a successful television series, ''[[Spenser for Hire]]'' which starred [[Robert Urich]], [[Avery Brooks]] and [[Barbara Stock]].\n\nIn 1994 Parker collaborated with Japanese photographer [[Kasho Kumagai]] on a [[coffee table book]] called ''Spenser's Boston'', exploring the city through Spenser's \"eyes\" via high quality, 4-color photos.  In addition to Parker's introduction, excerpts from several of the Spenser novels were included.<ref>[[The Tennessean]], 8 March 2009, Arts & Entertainment, p. 11</ref>\n\nParker created female detective Sunny Randall at the request of actress [[Helen Hunt]], who wanted him to write a part for her to play. He wrote the first book, and the film version was planned for 2000,<ref name=\"litweb\" /> but never materialized.<ref name=\"reporter\" />  However, his publisher liked the character and asked him to continue with the series.<ref name=\"reporter\" />\n\nAnother figure created by Parker was [[Jesse Stone (character)|Jesse Stone]], a troubled former [[Los Angeles Police Department|LAPD]] detective, who starts a new career as a police chief in a small New England town. Between 1997 and 2010, he wrote nine novels featuring Jesse Stone, all of which have been adapted as a series of TV movies by CBS starring [[Tom Selleck]] as Jesse Stone. \n\nAside from crime writing, Parker also produced several Western novels, including ''[[Appaloosa (novel)|Appaloosa]]'',<ref>This was adapted to film in 2008 by [[Ed Harris]], starring Harris (who also directed and co-wrote the screenplay), [[Viggo Mortensen]] and [[Jeremy Irons]]</ref> and children's books. Like Parker's Spenser series, his Westerns have received critical attention. Chris Dacus, who has written on other authors like Cormac McCarthy, has written of the intellectual depth and importance of Parker's Westerns in ''The Stoic Western Hero: Robert B. Parker's Westerns''.<ref>Dacus, Chris. The Stoic Western Hero: Robert B. Parker's Westerns. CDI: 2011. https://www.amazon.com/Stoic-Western-Hero-Westerns-Part-ebook/dp/B006C2C7H4/ref=sr_1_1?s=digital-text&ie=UTF8&qid=1378170886&sr=1-1&keywords=chris+dacus</ref>\n\nParker and his wife created an independent film company called Pearl Productions, based in [[Boston]]. It is named after their [[German Shorthaired Pointer|German short-haired pointer]], Pearl.<ref name=\"reporter\" />\n\n==Personal life==\nParker and his wife had two sons, David and Daniel.  Originally, the character of Spenser was to have been called \"David,\" but Parker didn't want to appear to favor one of his sons over the other.  Parker therefore omitted Spenser's first name entirely, and it was never revealed.\n\nParker and his wife, Joan, separated at one point but then came to an unusual arrangement. They lived in a three-story Victorian house just outside of Harvard Square; she lived on one floor and he on another, and they shared the middle floor. This living arrangement is mirrored in Spenser's private life: his girlfriend, Susan, had an aversion to marriage and living together full-time. Living separately suited them both, although they were fully committed to each other. Explaining the arrangement in an interview on ''[[CBS News Sunday Morning|CBS Sunday Morning]]'', Parker said, \"I want to make love to my wife for the rest of my life, but I never want to sleep with her again.\"\n\nHe had a great fondness for dogs, including German Pointers. Dogs were included in his Spenser stories, aging along with the character and appearing in the ongoing series of novels. The dogs were always named Pearl.<ref name=\"Globe 2013\">{{cite news|last1=Bissonette|first1=Zac|title=Robert B. Parker is dead. Long live Robert B. Parker!|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/magazine/2013/05/11/how-robert-parker-family-has-ensured-that-spenser-adventures-continue/Ae3xng4kdtXGUi1lawut3L/story.html|accessdate=13 January 2016|work=Boston Globe|date=May 12, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Awards===\nParker received three nominations and two [[Edgar Award]]s from the [[Mystery Writers of America]].  He received the first award, the \"Best Novel Award\" in 1977, for the fourth novel in the [[Spenser (character)|Spenser]] series, ''[[Promised Land (novel)|Promised Land]]''.<ref>[http://www.theedgars.com/edgarsDB/index.php \"Edgars\" database search for \"Grand Master\" award] at the [[Mystery Writers of America]]'s website . Retrieved February 2009.</ref>  In 1983 he received the [[Maltese Falcon Award#Falcon Awards|Maltese Falcon Award]], Japan, for ''[[Early Autumn (Parker novel)|Early Autumn]]''.  In 1990 he shared, with wife Joan, a nomination for \"Best Television Episode\" for the TV series ''B.L. Stryker''; however, the award went to David J. Burke and Alfonse Ruggiero Jr. for ''[[Wiseguy]]''.\n\nIn 2002 he received the ''Grand Master Award'' Edgar for his collective ''oeuvre''.<ref>theedgars.com database [http://www.theedgars.com/edgarsDB/index.php]. Retrieved February 2009.</ref>\n\nParker received the 2002 Joseph E. Connor Memorial Award from the Phi Alpha Tau Fraternity at Emerson College.  He was inducted into the fraternity as an honorary brother in Spring 2003.<ref>Phi Alpha Tau Fraternity [http://www.phialphatau.com/awards-scholarships/connor-award-recipients]. Retrieved November 2016.</ref>\n\nIn 2008 he was awarded the [[Gumshoe Awards|Gumshoe Lifetime Achievement Award]].\n\n==Death==\nParker was 77 when he died suddenly of a heart attack at his home in [[Cambridge, Massachusetts]] on January 18, 2010; discovered at his desk by his wife Joan, he had been working on a novel.<ref name=\"AP death notice\"/><ref name=Marquard>{{cite news\n| url = http://www.boston.com/news/local/breaking_news/2010/01/mystery_novelis.html| title = Mystery novelist Robert Parker dies at 77| author = Bryan Marquard| work = [[The Boston Globe]]| date = January 19, 2010| accessdate = January 20, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/01/19/AR2010011902195.html| title=Crime novelist, Spenser creator Robert B. Parker dies at 77| author= Patricia Sullivan| work=[[The Washington Post]]| date= January 20, 2010 | accessdate = January 20, 2010}}</ref>\n\nWritten by [[Ace Atkins]], the Spenser series continued following Parker's death. ''[[The Boston Globe]]'' wrote that while some people might have \"viewed the move as unseemly, those people didn\u2019t know Robert B. Parker, a man who, when asked how his books would be viewed in 50 years, replied: 'Don\u2019t know, don\u2019t care.' He was proud of his work, but he mainly saw writing as a means of providing a comfortable life for his family.\"<ref name=\"Globe 2013\" />\n\n\n==Bibliography==\n\n===Novels===\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\"\n! Title !! Year !! ISBN\n!style=\"width:7em;\"| Series\n!class=\"unsortable\"| Notes\n|-\n| ''[[The Godwulf Manuscript]]''\n| [[1973 in literature|1973]]\n| {{ISBNT|0-395-18011-2}}\n| Spenser 01\n| \n|-\n| ''[[God Save the Child]]''\n| [[1974 in literature|1974]]\n| {{ISBNT|0-395-19955-7}}\n| Spenser 02\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Mortal Stakes]]''\n| [[1975 in literature|1975]]\n| {{ISBNT|0-395-21969-8}}\n| Spenser 03\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Promised Land (novel)|Promised Land]]''\n| [[1976 in literature|1976]]\n| {{ISBNT|0-395-24771-3}}\n| Spenser 04\n| [[Edgar Award]], Best Novel\n|-\n| ''[[The Judas Goat]]''\n| [[1978 in literature|1978]]\n| {{ISBNT|0-395-26682-3}}\n| Spenser 05\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Wilderness (Parker novel)|Wilderness]]''\n| [[1979 in literature|1979]]\n| {{ISBNT|0-385-29108-6}}\n| \n| \n|-\n| ''[[Looking for Rachel Wallace]]''\n| [[1980 in literature|1980]]\n| {{ISBNT|0-385-28558-2}}\n| Spenser 06\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Early Autumn (Robert B. Parker novel)|Early Autumn]]''\n| 1980\n| {{ISBNT|0-385-28242-7}}\n| Spenser 07\n| 1983 [[Maltese Falcon Award#Falcon Awards|Maltese Falcon Award]]\n|-\n| ''[[A Savage Place]]''\n| [[1981 in literature|1981]]\n| {{ISBNT|0-385-28951-0}}\n| Spenser 08\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Ceremony (Robert B. Parker novel)|Ceremony]]''\n| [[1982 in literature|1982]]\n| {{ISBNT|0-385-28127-7}}\n| Spenser 09\n| \n|-\n| ''[[The Widening Gyre (novel)|The Widening Gyre]]''\n| [[1983 in literature|1983]]\n| {{ISBNT|0-385-29220-1}}\n| Spenser 10\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Love and Glory]]''\n| 1983\n| {{ISBNT|0-385-29261-9}}\n| \n| Set at Taft University\n|-\n| ''[[Valediction (novel)|Valediction]]''\n| [[1984 in literature|1984]]\n| {{ISBNT|0-385-29330-5}}\n| Spenser 11\n| \n|-\n| ''[[A Catskill Eagle]]''\n| [[1985 in literature|1985]]\n| {{ISBNT|0-385-29385-2}}\n| Spenser 12\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Taming a Sea-Horse]]''\n| [[1986 in literature|1986]]\n| {{ISBNT|0-385-29461-1}}\n| Spenser 13\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Pale Kings and Princes]]''\n| [[1987 in literature|1987]]\n| {{ISBNT|0-385-29538-3}}\n| Spenser 14\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Crimson Joy]]''\n| [[1988 in literature|1988]]\n| {{ISBNT|0-385-29668-1}}\n| Spenser 15\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Playmates (Robert B. Parker novel)|Playmates]]''\n| [[1989 in literature|1989]]\n| {{ISBNT|0-399-13463-8}}\n| Spenser 16\n| Set at Taft University\n|-\n| ''[[Poodle Springs]]''\n| 1989\n| {{ISBNT|0-399-13482-4}}\n| [[Philip Marlowe]] 1\n| Completing the 1958 [[Raymond Chandler]] novel - The first four chapters are written by [[Raymond Chandler]]\n|-\n| ''[[Stardust (1990 novel)|Stardust]]''\n| [[1990 in literature|1990]]\n| {{ISBNT|0-399-13537-5}}\n| Spenser 17\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Pastime (novel)|Pastime]]''\n| [[1991 in literature|1991]]\n| {{ISBNT|0-399-13630-4}}\n| Spenser 18\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Perchance to Dream (novel)|Perchance to Dream]]''\n| 1991\n| {{ISBNT|0-399-13580-4}}\n| Philip Marlowe 2\n| [[Sequel]] to ''[[The Big Sleep]]''\n|-\n| ''[[Double Deuce]]''\n| [[1992 in literature|1992]]\n| {{ISBNT|0-399-13754-8}}\n| Spenser 19\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Paper Doll (novel)|Paper Doll]]''\n| [[1993 in literature|1993]]\n| {{ISBNT|0-399-13818-8}}\n| Spenser 20\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Walking Shadow]]''\n| [[1994 in literature|1994]]\n| {{ISBNT|0-399-13961-3}}\n| Spenser 21\n| \n|-\n| ''[[All Our Yesterdays (novel)|All Our Yesterdays]]''\n| 1994 \n| {{ISBNT|0-385-30437-4}}\n| \n| \n|-\n| ''[[Thin Air (Parker novel)|Thin Air]]''\n| [[1995 in literature|1995]]\n| {{ISBNT|0-399-14063-8}}\n| Spenser 22\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Chance (Parker novel)|Chance]]''\n| [[1996 in literature|1996]]\n| {{ISBNT|0-399-14688-1}}\n| Spenser 23\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Small Vices]]''\n| [[1997 in literature|1997]]\n| {{ISBNT|0-399-14547-8}}\n| Spenser 24\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Night Passage (Parker novel)|Night Passage]]''\n| 1997\n| {{ISBNT|0-399-14304-1}}\n| Jesse Stone 1\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Trouble in Paradise (Parker novel)|Trouble in Paradise]]''\n| [[1998 in literature|1998]]\n| {{ISBNT|0-399-14433-1}}\n| Jesse Stone 2\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Sudden Mischief]]''\n| 1998\n| {{ISBNT|0-399-14696-2}}\n| Spenser 25\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Hush Money (novel)|Hush Money]]''\n| [[1999 in literature|1999]]\n| {{ISBNT|0-399-14458-7}}\n| Spenser 26\n| \n|-\n| ''Family Honor''\n| 1999\n| {{ISBNT|0-399-14566-4}}\n| Sunny Randall 1\n| \n|-\n| ''Perish Twice''\n| [[2000 in literature|2000]]\n| {{ISBNT|0-399-14668-7}}\n| Sunny Randall 2\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Hugger Mugger (novel)|Hugger Mugger]]''\n| 2000\n| {{ISBNT|0-399-14587-7}}\n| Spenser 27\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Gunman's Rhapsody]]''\n| [[2001 in literature|2001]]\n| {{ISBNT|0-399-14762-4}}\n| \n| [[Wyatt Earp]] in 1879\n|-\n| ''[[Death in Paradise (Parker novel)|Death in Paradise]]''\n| 2001\n| {{ISBNT|0-399-14779-9}}\n| Jesse Stone 3\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Potshot (novel)|Potshot]]''\n| 2001\n| {{ISBNT|0-399-14710-1}}\n| Spenser 28\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Widow's Walk (novel)|Widow's Walk]]''\n| [[2002 in literature|2002]]\n| {{ISBNT|0-399-14845-0}}\n| Spenser 29\n| \n|-\n| ''Shrink Rap''\n| 2002\n| {{ISBNT|0-399-14930-9}}\n| Sunny Randall 3\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Back Story (Parker novel)|Back Story]]''\n| [[2003 in literature|2003]]\n| {{ISBNT|0-399-14977-5}}\n| Spenser 30\n| Includes [[Jesse Stone novels|Jesse Stone]]\n|-\n| ''[[Stone Cold (Parker novel)|Stone Cold]]''\n| 2003\n| {{ISBNT|0-399-15087-0}}\n| Jesse Stone 4\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Bad Business (novel)|Bad Business]]''\n| [[2004 in literature|2004]]\n| {{ISBNT|0-399-15145-1}}\n| Spenser 31\n| \n|-\n| ''Melancholy Baby''\n| 2004\n| {{ISBNT|0-399-15218-0}}\n| Sunny Randall 4\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Double Play (novel)|Double Play]]''\n| 2004\n| {{ISBNT|0-399-15188-5}}\n| \n| \n|-\n| ''[[Cold Service]]''\n| [[2005 in literature|2005]]\n| {{ISBNT|0-399-15240-7}}\n| Spenser 32\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Appaloosa (novel)|Appaloosa]]''\n| 2005\n| {{ISBNT|0-399-15277-6}}\n| Cole & Hitch 1\n| \n|-\n|-\n| ''[[School Days (novel)|School Days]]''\n| 2005\n| {{ISBNT|0-399-15323-3}}\n| Spenser 33\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Hundred-Dollar Baby]]''\n| [[2006 in literature|2006]]\n| {{ISBNT|0-399-15376-4}}\n| Spenser 34\n| Also published as ''Dream Girl''\n|-\n| ''[[Sea Change (Parker novel)|Sea Change]]''\n| 2006\n| {{ISBNT|0-399-15267-9}}\n| Jesse Stone 5\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Blue Screen (Parker novel)|Blue Screen]]''\n| 2006 \n| {{ISBNT|0-399-15351-9}}\n| Sunny Randall 5\n| Includes [[Jesse Stone novels|Jesse Stone]]\n|-\n| ''[[High Profile (Parker novel)|High Profile]]''\n| [[2007 in literature|2007]]\n| {{ISBNT|0-399-15404-3}}\n| Jesse Stone 6\n| Includes Sunny Randall\n|-\n| ''[[Spare Change (Parker novel)|Spare Change]]''\n| 2007\n| {{ISBNT|0-399-15425-6}}\n| Sunny Randall 6\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Now and Then (Parker novel)|Now and Then]]''\n| 2007\n| {{ISBNT|0-399-15441-8}}\n| Spenser 35\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Edenville Owls]]''\n| 2007\n| {{ISBNT|0-399-24656-8}}\n| \n| \n|-\n| ''[[Stranger In Paradise (Parker novel)|Stranger In Paradise]]''\n| [[2008 in literature|2008]]\n| {{ISBNT|0-399-15460-4}}\n| Jesse Stone 7\n| \n|-\n| ''[[The Boxer and the Spy]]''\n| 2008\n| {{ISBNT|0-399-24775-0}}\n| \n| \n|-\n| ''[[Rough Weather (novel)|Rough Weather]]''\n| 2008\n| {{ISBNT|0-399-15519-8}}\n| Spenser 36\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Resolution (novel)|Resolution]]''\n| 2008\n| {{ISBNT|0-399-15504-X}}\n| Cole & Hitch 2\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Brimstone (Robert B. Parker novel)|Brimstone]]''\n| [[2009 in literature|2009]]\n| {{ISBNT|0-399-15571-6}}\n| Cole & Hitch 3\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Chasing the Bear]]''\n| 2009\n| {{ISBNT|0-399-24776-9}}\n| Spenser 37 (prequel)\n| \"Young Spenser\"\n|- \n| ''[[Night and Day (Parker novel)|Night and Day]]''\n| 2009\n| {{ISBNT|0-399-15541-4}}\n| Jesse Stone 8\n| Includes Sunny Randall\n|-\n| ''[[The Professional (novel)|The Professional]]''\n| 2009\n| {{ISBNT|0-399-15594-5}}\n| Spenser 38\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Split Image (Parker novel)|Split Image]]''\n| [[2010 in literature|2010]]\n| {{ISBNT|0-399-15623-2}}\n| Jesse Stone 9\n| Published posthumously, includes Sunny Randall\n|-\n| ''[[Blue-Eyed Devil (Robert B. Parker novel)|Blue-Eyed Devil]]''\n| 2010\n| {{ISBNT|0-399-15648-8}}\n| Cole & Hitch 4\n| Published posthumously\n|-\n| ''[[Painted Ladies (Parker novel)|Painted Ladies]]''\n| 2010\n| {{ISBNT|0-399-15685-2}}\n| Spenser 39\n| Published posthumously\n|-\n| ''[[Sixkill]]''\n| [[2011 in literature|2011]]\n| {{ISBNT|0-399-15726-3}}\n| Spenser 40\n| Published posthumously\n|-\n| ''Silent Night''\n| [[2013 in literature|2013]]\n| {{ISBNT|0-425-27161-7}}\n| Spenser 41\n| Unfinished, completed by literary agent Helen Brann\n|-\n|}\n\n====Series continuations====\nAfter Parker died the owners of his estate decided, together with Parker's publishers, to continue his series: Jesse Stone, Spenser and Virgil Cole & Everett Hitch.\n\nThe ''[[Jesse Stone (character)#Novels|Jesse Stone]]'' series has been continued, through 2016 with six novels, one a year, the first three by Parker's longtime friend and collaborator, [[Michael Brandman]], and the last three by [[Reed Farrel Coleman]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.facebook.com/notes/robert-b-parker/the-putnam-press-release/210748698944997 |title=The Putnam Press Release |author=Estate of Robert B. Parker |date=27 April 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.boston.com/ae/celebrity/articles/2011/04/28/parkers_series_live_on/?rss_id=Boston.com+--+Latest+celebrity+headlines |title=Parker\u2019s series live on |first=Mark |last=Shanahan |author2=[[Meredith Goldstein]]  |work=The Boston Globe |date=28 April 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe ''[[Spenser (character)|Spenser]]'' novels have continued with the one Parker was working on at his death completed by his long time literary agent Helen Brann, and through 2016 with five others by journalist/writer [[Ace Atkins]].\n\nParker's ''Virgil Cole and Everett Hitch'' series has been continued by actor and screenwriter [[Robert Knott]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.facebook.com/RobertBParkerAuthor/posts/468860899799971 |title=Facebook post |author=Estate of Robert B. Parker|date=9 August 2012}}</ref> with three novels published through 2016.\n\nThe ''Sunny Randall'' series received a 7th installment titled ''Blood Feud'' on November 27, 2018 with an 8th titled ''Grudge Match'' scheduled for a May 4, 2020 release.  Written by long time friend of Parker, sports journalist, and bestselling author, [[Mike Lupica]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://therealbookspy.com/2018/03/26/mike-lupica-set-to-continue-robert-b-parkers-sunny-randall-series-blood-feud-due-out-in-november/ |title=Mike Lupica Set To Continue Robert B. Parker\u2019s Sunny Randall Series; \u2018Blood Feud\u2019 Due Out In November |author=Ryan Steck |date=26 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Non-fiction===\n* ''Sports Illustrated Training with Weights'' (with John R. Marsh) (1974) {{ISBN|1-56800-032-4}}\n* ''Three Weeks in Spring'' (with Joan H. Parker) (1982) {{ISBN|0-395-26282-8}}\n* ''A Year At The Races'' (with Joan H. Parker) (1990) {{ISBN|0-670-82678-2}}\n* ''Spenser's Boston'' (with Kasho Kumagai) (1994) {{ISBN|1-883402-50-6}} {{ISBN|978-1883402501}}\n\n===Short fiction===\n\"Surrogate\"' (1991)\" A short story published in the crime anthology ''New Crimes 3'' {{ISBN|0-88184-737-2}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscategory|Robert Brown Parker}}\n* {{official|http://www.robertbparker.net/}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070328193045/http://www.iblist.com/author1762.htm Robert B. Parker] at [[Internet Book List]]/[https://web.archive.org/web/20070207044954/http://www.iblist.com/ Internet Book List :: Home]\n* [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/culture-obituaries/books-obituaries/7038200/Robert-B-Parker.html Robert B Parker] \u2013 Daily Telegraph obituary\n* \"Looking for Robert B. Parker: A Fond Farewell to the Man Who Saved P.I. Fiction,\" [http://therapsheet.blogspot.com/2010/01/looking-for-robert-b-parker-fond.html Part I] and [http://therapsheet.blogspot.com/2010/01/looking-for-robert-b-parker-fond_25.html Part II] - The Rap Sheet\n\n{{Spenser}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Parker, Robert B.}}\n[[Category:1932 births]]\n[[Category:2010 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American novelists]]\n[[Category:American mystery writers]]\n[[Category:Boston University College of Arts and Sciences alumni]]\n[[Category:Colby College alumni]]\n[[Category:Anthony Award winners]]\n[[Category:Edgar Award winners]]\n[[Category:Maltese Falcon Award winners]]\n[[Category:Shamus Award winners]]\n[[Category:Northeastern University faculty]]\n[[Category:Writers from Cambridge, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Writers from Springfield, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:American male novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male writers]]\n[[Category:Novelists from Massachusetts]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American crime writer}}\n{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| name = Robert B. Parker\n| image = Robert_B._Parker_at_Manchester_Library.jpg\n| imagesize =\n| caption = Parker in 2006\n| pseudonym =\n| birth_name = Robert Brown Parker\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1932|9|17}}\n| birth_place = [[Springfield, Massachusetts]], [[U.S.]]\n| death_date = {{death date and age|2010|1|18|1932|9|17}}<ref name=\"AP death notice\">{{cite news|url=http://www.bostonherald.com/entertainment/books/view.bg?articleid=1226710&pos=breaking |title='Spenser' novelist Robert Parker dies in Cambridge |agency=[[Associated Press]] |work=[[Boston Herald]] |date=2010-01-19 |accessdate=2010-01-19}}</ref>\n| death_place = [[Cambridge, Massachusetts]], [[U.S.]]\n| occupation = Novelist\n| period = 1974\u20132010\n| genre = [[Crime fiction|Detective fiction]], [[Western fiction]]\n| subject =\n| movement =\n| spouse = Joan Hall Parker (1956 \u20132010)\n| partner =\n| children = 2 sons\n| relatives =\n| signature =\n| website = {{URL|robertbparker.net}}\n}}\n'''Robert Brown Parker''' (September 17, 1932 &ndash; January 18, 2010) was an American writer of fiction, primarily of the mystery/detective genre.  His most famous works were the 40 novels written about the fictional  [[private detective]] [[Spenser (character)|Spenser]]. [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] television network developed the television series ''[[Spenser: For Hire]]'' based on the character in the mid-1980s; a [[Spenser (TV movies)|series of TV movies]] based on the character was also produced. His works incorporate encyclopedic knowledge of the [[Boston]] metropolitan area.<ref>{{cite book  | last = Geherin  | first = David  | title = Sons of Sam Spade: the private-eye novel in the 70s: Robert B. Parker, Roger L. Simon, Andrew Bergman  | publisher = Ungar  | year = c. 1980  | isbn = 0-8044-2231-1 }}</ref> The Spenser novels have been cited by critics and bestselling authors such as [[Robert Crais]], [[Harlan Coben]], and [[Dennis Lehane]]<ref>\"His Spenser Novels Saved Detective Fiction\" by Tom Nolan, ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'' [https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748703837004575013104258735756]</ref> as not only influencing their own work but reviving and changing the detective genre.<ref>\"Robert B. Parker left a mark on the detective novel\" by Sarah Weinman, ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' [http://articles.latimes.com/2010/jan/20/entertainment/la-et-robert-parker20-2010jan20]</ref>  \n\nParker also wrote two other series based on an individual character:  He wrote nine novels based on the fictional character [[Jesse Stone (character)|Jesse Stone]], a Los Angeles police officer who moves to a small New England town, and six novels based on the fictional character Sunny Randall, a female private investigator. Parker wrote four Westerns starring the duo Virgil Cole and Everett Hitch. The first, ''[[Appaloosa (novel)|Appaloosa]]'', was made into a film starring [[Ed Harris]].\n\n==Early life==\nParker was born in [[Springfield, Massachusetts]].<ref name=\"litweb\">[http://www.litweb.net/biogs/parker_robert_b.html Robert B. Parker biography] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100211045212/http://litweb.net/biogs/parker_robert_b.html |date=2010-02-11 }} from Litweb.net</ref> In 1956 Parker married Joan H. Parker, whom he claimed to have met as a toddler at a birthday party.<ref name=\"Times obit\">{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/01/20/books/20parker.html | title=Robert B. Parker, the Prolific Writer Who Created Spenser, Is Dead at 77 | author= Bruce Weber | date= January 20, 2010 | work= [[The New York Times]] | accessdate = January 20, 2010}}</ref> They spent their childhoods in the same neighborhood.<ref>{{cite web|author=Jules Older |url=http://www.yankeemagazine.com/issues/2003-10/robert-parker |title=Robert B. Parker 2003 Interview |work=Yankee Magazine |date=October 2003 |accessdate=2010-02-23}}</ref>\n\nAfter earning a BA degree from [[Colby College]] in [[Waterville, Maine]], Parker served as a soldier in the [[United States Army|US Army]] Infantry in [[Korea]].  In 1957, he earned his master's degree in [[English literature]] from [[Boston University]] and then worked in advertising and technical writing until 1962.<ref name=\"litweb\" /> Parker received a PhD in English literature from Boston University in 1971.<ref name=\"reporter\">[http://www.bookreporter.com/authors/au-parker-robert.asp Author Profile: Robert B. Parker] from BookReporter.com</ref>  His dissertation, titled \"The Violent Hero, Wilderness Heritage and Urban Reality,\" discussed the exploits of fictional private-eye heroes created by [[Dashiell Hammett]], [[Raymond Chandler]], and [[Ross Macdonald]].<ref name=\"litweb\" />\n\n==Career==\nParker wrote his first novel<ref name=\"reporter\" /> in 1971 while teaching at [[Northeastern University]].<!--The article without the disambiguation is about the school in Boston.--> He became a full professor in 1976, and turned to full-time writing in 1979 with five Spenser novels to his credit.<ref name=\"litweb\" />\n\nParker's popular [[Spenser (character)|Spenser]] novels are known for his characters of varied races and religions.  According to critic Christina Nunez, Parker's \"inclusion of [characters of] other races and sexual persuasions\" lends his writings a \"more modern feel\".<ref>{{cite web| author=Christina Nunez |url=http://www.barnesandnoble.com/writers/writerdetails.asp?cid=802368 |title=Robert B. Parker Biography |work=Barnes and Noble |accessdate=2010-02-23}}</ref>  For example, the ''Spenser'' series characters include Hawk and Chollo, African-American and Mexican-American, respectively, as well as Spenser's Jewish girlfriend, Susan, various Russians, Ukrainians, Chinese, a gay cop, Lee Farrell, and even a gay mob boss, Gino Fish.<ref>See nearly the entire Spenser series for Hawk, whose prominence in the plots increases with each book; for Chollo, ''Stardust'', ''[[Pot Shot]]'', and ''Now and Then''; ''[[Cold Service]]'' features Ukrainian and Russian mobsters; and ''[[Walking Shadow]]'', which explores [[Tong (organization)|Chinese tongs]] and includes a Chinese-American translator named Mei Ling who has a relationship with Hawk; see ''[[Chance (Parker novel)|Chance]]'' for Gino Fish, who also crosses over into the first Jesse Stone novel.</ref> The homosexuality of both his sons gave his writing \"[a] sensibility,\" Ms. Nunez feels, \"[which] strengthens Parker's sensibility [toward gays].\"  In 1985 ''Spenser'' was made into a successful television series, ''[[Spenser for Hire]]'' which starred [[Robert Urich]], [[Avery Brooks]] and [[Barbara Stock]].\n\nIn 1994 Parker collaborated with Japanese photographer [[Kasho Kumagai]] on a [[coffee table book]] called ''Spenser's Boston'', exploring the city through Spenser's \"eyes\" via high quality, 4-color photos.  In addition to Parker's introduction, excerpts from several of the Spenser novels were included.<ref>[[The Tennessean]], 8 March 2009, Arts & Entertainment, p. 11</ref>\n\nParker created female detective Sunny Randall at the request of actress [[Helen Hunt]], who wanted him to write a part for her to play. He wrote the first book, and the film version was planned for 2000,<ref name=\"litweb\" /> but never materialized.<ref name=\"reporter\" />  However, his publisher liked the character and asked him to continue with the series.<ref name=\"reporter\" />\n\nAnother figure created by Parker was [[Jesse Stone (character)|Jesse Stone]], a troubled former [[Los Angeles Police Department|LAPD]] detective, who starts a new career as a police chief in a small New England town. Between 1997 and 2010, he wrote nine novels featuring Jesse Stone, all of which have been adapted as a series of TV movies by CBS starring [[Tom Selleck]] as Jesse Stone. \n\nAside from crime writing, Parker also produced several Western novels, including ''[[Appaloosa (novel)|Appaloosa]]'',<ref>This was adapted to film in 2008 by [[Ed Harris]], starring Harris (who also directed and co-wrote the screenplay), [[Viggo Mortensen]] and [[Jeremy Irons]]</ref> and children's books. Like Parker's Spenser series, his Westerns have received critical attention. Chris Dacus, who has written on other authors like Cormac McCarthy, has written of the intellectual depth and importance of Parker's Westerns in ''The Stoic Western Hero: Robert B. Parker's Westerns''.<ref>Dacus, Chris. The Stoic Western Hero: Robert B. Parker's Westerns. CDI: 2011. https://www.amazon.com/Stoic-Western-Hero-Westerns-Part-ebook/dp/B006C2C7H4/ref=sr_1_1?s=digital-text&ie=UTF8&qid=1378170886&sr=1-1&keywords=chris+dacus</ref>\n\nParker and his wife created an independent film company called Pearl Productions, based in [[Boston]]. It is named after their [[German Shorthaired Pointer|German short-haired pointer]], Pearl.<ref name=\"reporter\" />\n\n==Personal life==\nParker and his wife had two sons, David and Daniel.  Originally, the character of Spenser was to have been called \"David,\" but Parker didn't want to appear to favor one of his sons over the other.  Parker therefore omitted Spenser's first name entirely, and it was never revealed.\n\nParker and his wife, Joan, separated at one point but then came to an unusual arrangement. They lived in a three-story Victorian house just outside of Harvard Square; she lived on one floor and he on another, and they shared the middle floor. This living arrangement is mirrored in Spenser's private life: his girlfriend, Susan, had an aversion to marriage and living together full-time. Living separately suited them both, although they were fully committed to each other. Explaining the arrangement in an interview on ''[[CBS News Sunday Morning|CBS Sunday Morning]]'', Parker said, \"I want to make love to my wife for the rest of my life, but I never want to sleep with her again.\"\n\nHe had a great fondness for dogs, including German Pointers. Dogs were included in his Spenser stories, aging along with the character and appearing in the ongoing series of novels. The dogs were always named Pearl.<ref name=\"Globe 2013\">{{cite news|last1=Bissonette|first1=Zac|title=Robert B. Parker is dead. Long live Robert B. Parker!|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/magazine/2013/05/11/how-robert-parker-family-has-ensured-that-spenser-adventures-continue/Ae3xng4kdtXGUi1lawut3L/story.html|accessdate=13 January 2016|work=Boston Globe|date=May 12, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Awards===\nParker received three nominations and two [[Edgar Award]]s from the [[Mystery Writers of America]].  He received the first award, the \"Best Novel Award\" in 1977, for the fourth novel in the [[Spenser (character)|Spenser]] series, ''[[Promised Land (novel)|Promised Land]]''.<ref>[http://www.theedgars.com/edgarsDB/index.php \"Edgars\" database search for \"Grand Master\" award] at the [[Mystery Writers of America]]'s website . Retrieved February 2009.</ref>  In 1983 he received the [[Maltese Falcon Award#Falcon Awards|Maltese Falcon Award]], Japan, for ''[[Early Autumn (Parker novel)|Early Autumn]]''.  In 1990 he shared, with wife Joan, a nomination for \"Best Television Episode\" for the TV series ''B.L. Stryker''; however, the award went to David J. Burke and Alfonse Ruggiero Jr. for ''[[Wiseguy]]''.\n\nIn 2002 he received the ''Grand Master Award'' Edgar for his collective ''oeuvre''.<ref>theedgars.com database [http://www.theedgars.com/edgarsDB/index.php]. Retrieved February 2009.</ref>\n\nParker received the 2002 Joseph E. Connor Memorial Award from the Phi Alpha Tau Fraternity at Emerson College.  He was inducted into the fraternity as an honorary brother in Spring 2003.<ref>Phi Alpha Tau Fraternity [http://www.phialphatau.com/awards-scholarships/connor-award-recipients]. Retrieved November 2016.</ref>\n\nIn 2008 he was awarded the [[Gumshoe Awards|Gumshoe Lifetime Achievement Award]].\n\n==Death==\nParker was 77 when he died suddenly of a heart attack at his home in [[Cambridge, Massachusetts]] on January 18, 2010; discovered at his desk by his wife Joan, he had been working on a novel.<ref name=\"AP death notice\"/><ref name=Marquard>{{cite news\n| url = http://www.boston.com/news/local/breaking_news/2010/01/mystery_novelis.html| title = Mystery novelist Robert Parker dies at 77| author = Bryan Marquard| work = [[The Boston Globe]]| date = January 19, 2010| accessdate = January 20, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/01/19/AR2010011902195.html| title=Crime novelist, Spenser creator Robert B. Parker dies at 77| author= Patricia Sullivan| work=[[The Washington Post]]| date= January 20, 2010 | accessdate = January 20, 2010}}</ref>\n\nWritten by [[Ace Atkins]], the Spenser series continued following Parker's death. ''[[The Boston Globe]]'' wrote that while some people might have \"viewed the move as unseemly, those people didn\u2019t know Robert B. Parker, a man who, when asked how his books would be viewed in 50 years, replied: 'Don\u2019t know, don\u2019t care.' He was proud of his work, but he mainly saw writing as a means of providing a comfortable life for his family.\"<ref name=\"Globe 2013\" />\n\n\n==Bibliography==\n\n===Novels===\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\"\n! Title !! Year !! ISBN\n!style=\"width:7em;\"| Series\n!class=\"unsortable\"| Notes\n|-\n| ''[[The Godwulf Manuscript]]''\n| [[1973 in literature|1973]]\n| {{ISBNT|0-395-18011-2}}\n| Spenser 01\n| \n|-\n| ''[[God Save the Child]]''\n| [[1974 in literature|1974]]\n| {{ISBNT|0-395-19955-7}}\n| Spenser 02\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Mortal Stakes]]''\n| [[1975 in literature|1975]]\n| {{ISBNT|0-395-21969-8}}\n| Spenser 03\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Promised Land (novel)|Promised Land]]''\n| [[1976 in literature|1976]]\n| {{ISBNT|0-395-24771-3}}\n| Spenser 04\n| [[Edgar Award]], Best Novel\n|-\n| ''[[The Judas Goat]]''\n| [[1978 in literature|1978]]\n| {{ISBNT|0-395-26682-3}}\n| Spenser 05\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Wilderness (Parker novel)|Wilderness]]''\n| [[1979 in literature|1979]]\n| {{ISBNT|0-385-29108-6}}\n| \n| \n|-\n| ''[[Looking for Rachel Wallace]]''\n| [[1980 in literature|1980]]\n| {{ISBNT|0-385-28558-2}}\n| Spenser 06\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Early Autumn (Robert B. Parker novel)|Early Autumn]]''\n| 1980\n| {{ISBNT|0-385-28242-7}}\n| Spenser 07\n| 1983 [[Maltese Falcon Award#Falcon Awards|Maltese Falcon Award]]\n|-\n| ''[[A Savage Place]]''\n| [[1981 in literature|1981]]\n| {{ISBNT|0-385-28951-0}}\n| Spenser 08\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Ceremony (Robert B. Parker novel)|Ceremony]]''\n| [[1982 in literature|1982]]\n| {{ISBNT|0-385-28127-7}}\n| Spenser 09\n| \n|-\n| ''[[The Widening Gyre (novel)|The Widening Gyre]]''\n| [[1983 in literature|1983]]\n| {{ISBNT|0-385-29220-1}}\n| Spenser 10\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Love and Glory]]''\n| 1983\n| {{ISBNT|0-385-29261-9}}\n| \n| Set at Taft University\n|-\n| ''[[Valediction (novel)|Valediction]]''\n| [[1984 in literature|1984]]\n| {{ISBNT|0-385-29330-5}}\n| Spenser 11\n| \n|-\n| ''[[A Catskill Eagle]]''\n| [[1985 in literature|1985]]\n| {{ISBNT|0-385-29385-2}}\n| Spenser 12\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Taming a Sea-Horse]]''\n| [[1986 in literature|1986]]\n| {{ISBNT|0-385-29461-1}}\n| Spenser 13\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Pale Kings and Princes]]''\n| [[1987 in literature|1987]]\n| {{ISBNT|0-385-29538-3}}\n| Spenser 14\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Crimson Joy]]''\n| [[1988 in literature|1988]]\n| {{ISBNT|0-385-29668-1}}\n| Spenser 15\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Playmates (Robert B. Parker novel)|Playmates]]''\n| [[1989 in literature|1989]]\n| {{ISBNT|0-399-13463-8}}\n| Spenser 16\n| Set at Taft University\n|-\n| ''[[Poodle Springs]]''\n| 1989\n| {{ISBNT|0-399-13482-4}}\n| [[Philip Marlowe]] 1\n| Completing the 1958 [[Raymond Chandler]] novel - The first four chapters are written by [[Raymond Chandler]]\n|-\n| ''[[Stardust (1990 novel)|Stardust]]''\n| [[1990 in literature|1990]]\n| {