se (Parker novel)|Death in Paradise]]''\n| 2001\n| {{ISBNT|0-399-14779-9}}\n| Jesse Stone 3\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Potshot (novel)|Potshot]]''\n| 2001\n| {{ISBNT|0-399-14710-1}}\n| Spenser 28\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Widow's Walk (novel)|Widow's Walk]]''\n| [[2002 in literature|2002]]\n| {{ISBNT|0-399-14845-0}}\n| Spenser 29\n| \n|-\n| ''Shrink Rap''\n| 2002\n| {{ISBNT|0-399-14930-9}}\n| Sunny Randall 3\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Back Story (Parker novel)|Back Story]]''\n| [[2003 in literature|2003]]\n| {{ISBNT|0-399-14977-5}}\n| Spenser 30\n| Includes [[Jesse Stone novels|Jesse Stone]]\n|-\n| ''[[Stone Cold (Parker novel)|Stone Cold]]''\n| 2003\n| {{ISBNT|0-399-15087-0}}\n| Jesse Stone 4\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Bad Business (novel)|Bad Business]]''\n| [[2004 in literature|2004]]\n| {{ISBNT|0-399-15145-1}}\n| Spenser 31\n| \n|-\n| ''Melancholy Baby''\n| 2004\n| {{ISBNT|0-399-15218-0}}\n| Sunny Randall 4\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Double Play (novel)|Double Play]]''\n| 2004\n| {{ISBNT|0-399-15188-5}}\n| \n| \n|-\n| ''[[Cold Service]]''\n| [[2005 in literature|2005]]\n| {{ISBNT|0-399-15240-7}}\n| Spenser 32\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Appaloosa (novel)|Appaloosa]]''\n| 2005\n| {{ISBNT|0-399-15277-6}}\n| Cole & Hitch 1\n| \n|-\n|-\n| ''[[School Days (novel)|School Days]]''\n| 2005\n| {{ISBNT|0-399-15323-3}}\n| Spenser 33\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Hundred-Dollar Baby]]''\n| [[2006 in literature|2006]]\n| {{ISBNT|0-399-15376-4}}\n| Spenser 34\n| Also published as ''Dream Girl''\n|-\n| ''[[Sea Change (Parker novel)|Sea Change]]''\n| 2006\n| {{ISBNT|0-399-15267-9}}\n| Jesse Stone 5\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Blue Screen (Parker novel)|Blue Screen]]''\n| 2006 \n| {{ISBNT|0-399-15351-9}}\n| Sunny Randall 5\n| Includes [[Jesse Stone novels|Jesse Stone]]\n|-\n| ''[[High Profile (Parker novel)|High Profile]]''\n| [[2007 in literature|2007]]\n| {{ISBNT|0-399-15404-3}}\n| Jesse Stone 6\n| Includes Sunny Randall\n|-\n| ''[[Spare Change (Parker novel)|Spare Change]]''\n| 2007\n| {{ISBNT|0-399-15425-6}}\n| Sunny Randall 6\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Now and Then (Parker novel)|Now and Then]]''\n| 2007\n| {{ISBNT|0-399-15441-8}}\n| Spenser 35\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Edenville Owls]]''\n| 2007\n| {{ISBNT|0-399-24656-8}}\n| \n| \n|-\n| ''[[Stranger In Paradise (Parker novel)|Stranger In Paradise]]''\n| [[2008 in literature|2008]]\n| {{ISBNT|0-399-15460-4}}\n| Jesse Stone 7\n| \n|-\n| ''[[The Boxer and the Spy]]''\n| 2008\n| {{ISBNT|0-399-24775-0}}\n| \n| \n|-\n| ''[[Rough Weather (novel)|Rough Weather]]''\n| 2008\n| {{ISBNT|0-399-15519-8}}\n| Spenser 36\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Resolution (novel)|Resolution]]''\n| 2008\n| {{ISBNT|0-399-15504-X}}\n| Cole & Hitch 2\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Brimstone (Robert B. Parker novel)|Brimstone]]''\n| [[2009 in literature|2009]]\n| {{ISBNT|0-399-15571-6}}\n| Cole & Hitch 3\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Chasing the Bear]]''\n| 2009\n| {{ISBNT|0-399-24776-9}}\n| Spenser 37 (prequel)\n| \"Young Spenser\"\n|- \n| ''[[Night and Day (Parker novel)|Night and Day]]''\n| 2009\n| {{ISBNT|0-399-15541-4}}\n| Jesse Stone 8\n| Includes Sunny Randall\n|-\n| ''[[The Professional (novel)|The Professional]]''\n| 2009\n| {{ISBNT|0-399-15594-5}}\n| Spenser 38\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Split Image (Parker novel)|Split Image]]''\n| [[2010 in literature|2010]]\n| {{ISBNT|0-399-15623-2}}\n| Jesse Stone 9\n| Published posthumously, includes Sunny Randall\n|-\n| ''[[Blue-Eyed Devil (Robert B. Parker novel)|Blue-Eyed Devil]]''\n| 2010\n| {{ISBNT|0-399-15648-8}}\n| Cole & Hitch 4\n| Published posthumously\n|-\n| ''[[Painted Ladies (Parker novel)|Painted Ladies]]''\n| 2010\n| {{ISBNT|0-399-15685-2}}\n| Spenser 39\n| Published posthumously\n|-\n| ''[[Sixkill]]''\n| [[2011 in literature|2011]]\n| {{ISBNT|0-399-15726-3}}\n| Spenser 40\n| Published posthumously\n|-\n| ''Silent Night''\n| [[2013 in literature|2013]]\n| {{ISBNT|0-425-27161-7}}\n| Spenser 41\n| Unfinished, completed by literary agent Helen Brann\n|-\n|}\n\n====Series continuations====\nAfter Parker died the owners of his estate decided, together with Parker's publishers, to continue his series: Jesse Stone, Spenser and Virgil Cole & Everett Hitch.\n\nThe ''[[Jesse Stone (character)#Novels|Jesse Stone]]'' series has been continued, through 2016 with six novels, one a year, the first three by Parker's longtime friend and collaborator, [[Michael Brandman]], and the last three by [[Reed Farrel Coleman]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.facebook.com/notes/robert-b-parker/the-putnam-press-release/210748698944997 |title=The Putnam Press Release |author=Estate of Robert B. Parker |date=27 April 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.boston.com/ae/celebrity/articles/2011/04/28/parkers_series_live_on/?rss_id=Boston.com+--+Latest+celebrity+headlines |title=Parker\u2019s series live on |first=Mark |last=Shanahan |author2=[[Meredith Goldstein]]  |work=The Boston Globe |date=28 April 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe ''[[Spenser (character)|Spenser]]'' novels have continued with the one Parker was working on at his death completed by his long time literary agent Helen Brann, and through 2016 with five others by journalist/writer [[Ace Atkins]].\n\nParker's ''Virgil Cole and Everett Hitch'' series has been continued by actor and screenwriter [[Robert Knott]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.facebook.com/RobertBParkerAuthor/posts/468860899799971 |title=Facebook post |author=Estate of Robert B. Parker|date=9 August 2012}}</ref> with three novels published through 2016.\n\nThe ''Sunny Randall'' series received a 7th installment titled ''Blood Feud'' on November 27, 2018 with an 8th titled ''Grudge Match'' scheduled for a May 4, 2020 release.  Written by long time friend of Parker, sports journalist, and bestselling author, [[Mike Lupica]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://therealbookspy.com/2018/03/26/mike-lupica-set-to-continue-robert-b-parkers-sunny-randall-series-blood-feud-due-out-in-november/ |title=Mike Lupica Set To Continue Robert B. Parker\u2019s Sunny Randall Series; \u2018Blood Feud\u2019 Due Out In November |author=Ryan Steck |date=26 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Non-fiction===\n* ''Sports Illustrated Training with Weights'' (with John R. Marsh) (1974) {{ISBN|1-56800-032-4}}\n* ''Three Weeks in Spring'' (with Joan H. Parker) (1982) {{ISBN|0-395-26282-8}}\n* ''A Year At The Races'' (with Joan H. Parker) (1990) {{ISBN|0-670-82678-2}}\n* ''Spenser's Boston'' (with Kasho Kumagai) (1994) {{ISBN|1-883402-50-6}} {{ISBN|978-1883402501}}\n\n===Short fiction===\n\"Surrogate\"' (1991)\" A short story published in the crime anthology ''New Crimes 3'' {{ISBN|0-88184-737-2}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscategory|Robert Brown Parker}}\n* {{official|http://www.robertbparker.net/}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070328193045/http://www.iblist.com/author1762.htm Robert B. Parker] at [[Internet Book List]]/[https://web.archive.org/web/20070207044954/http://www.iblist.com/ Internet Book List :: Home]\n* [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/culture-obituaries/books-obituaries/7038200/Robert-B-Parker.html Robert B Parker] \u2013 Daily Telegraph obituary\n* \"Looking for Robert B. Parker: A Fond Farewell to the Man Who Saved P.I. Fiction,\" [http://therapsheet.blogspot.com/2010/01/looking-for-robert-b-parker-fond.html Part I] and [http://therapsheet.blogspot.com/2010/01/looking-for-robert-b-parker-fond_25.html Part II] - The Rap Sheet\n\n{{Spenser}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Parker, Robert B.}}\n[[Category:1932 births]]\n[[Category:2010 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American novelists]]\n[[Category:American mystery writers]]\n[[Category:Boston University College of Arts and Sciences alumni]]\n[[Category:Colby College alumni]]\n[[Category:Anthony Award winners]]\n[[Category:Edgar Award winners]]\n[[Category:Maltese Falcon Award winners]]\n[[Category:Shamus Award winners]]\n[[Category:Northeastern University faculty]]\n[[Category:Writers from Cambridge, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Writers from Springfield, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:American male novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male writers]]\n[[Category:Novelists from Massachusetts]]\n", "name_user": "2606:a000:6a84:d300:1d97:12c9:3b2:cb8d", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(i fixed garammar)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robert_B._Parker"}
{"title_page": "Partha Sarathi Gupta", "text_new": "{{Infobox academic\n| honorific_prefix   = Professor\n| name               = Partha Sarathi Gupta\n| honorific_suffix   = \n| image              = Partha sarathi Gupta.jpg\n| image_size         = \n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| native_name        = \n| native_name_lang   = \n| birth_name         = <!-- use only if different from full/othernames -->\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date |1934|08|05}}\n| birth_place        = \n| death_date         = {{Death date and age|1999|08|10|1934|08|05}}\n| death_place        = [[New Delhi]]\n| death_cause        = \n| region             = Delhi\n| nationality        = Indian\n| citizenship        = \n| residence          = New Delhi\n| other_names        = \n| occupation         = Professor of British and European History, [[Delhi University]]\n| period             = \n| known_for          = \n| home_town          = \n| title              = Ex-President, [[Indian History Congress]] \n| boards             = <!--board or similar positions extraneous to main occupation-->\n| spouse             = \n| partner            = \n| children           = \n| parents            =\n| relatives          =\n| awards             = [[Ishan Uday]]<br/> Smuts Fellow in Commonwealth History at [[Cambridge University]] (1980-1981)<br/> Fellow of the Royal Historical Society <br/>Editorial Advisory Board Member of the Journal of Imperial and Commonwealth History\n| website            = \n| education          = BA , MA, M Phil, PhD\n| alma_mater         = [[Presidency College, Calcutta]]<small>(BA)</small> <br/> [[Queen's College, Oxford]] <small>(MA, PhD)</small>\n| thesis_title       = \n| thesis_url         = \n| thesis_year        = 1956\n| school_tradition   = Liberalism\n| doctoral_advisor   = [[Henry Pelling]]\n| academic_advisors  = [[Christopher Hill (historian)|Christopher Hill]] <br/> [[Keith Thomas (historian)|Keith Thomas]]\n| influences         = \n| era                = 1914-1964\n| discipline         = [[Historian]]\n| sub_discipline     = Imperialism And The British [[Labour Movement]], Commonwealth History, [[English Civil War]] , Documents For The Movement For Independence In India, \n| workplaces         = \n| doctoral_students  = <!--only those with WP articles-->\n| notable_students   = \n| main_interests     = \n| notable_works      = Imperialism And The British Labour Movement, 1914-1964<br/> Towards Freedom: Documents For The Movement For Independence In India, 1943-44\n| notable_ideas      = \n| influenced         = <!--must be referenced from a third-party source-->\n| signature          = \n| signature_alt      = \n| signature_size     = \n| footnotes          = \n}}\n'''Partha Sarathi Gupta''' (5 August 1934 \u2013 10 August 1999) was an [[India]]n professor of British and European history at [[Delhi University]] and president of the [[Indian History Congress]]. He was firstborn son of [[Ashoka Gupta]] and Saibal Gupta, an [[Indian Civil Services]] officer in Bengal state of British India. His childhood memory of watching [[Mahatma Gandhi]]'s walk through riot-torn Noakhali in 1946 where his mother joined in the walk had a long-lasting impact. He was awarded Eshan scholarship for the highest marks in [[West Bengal]] in [[Presidency College, Kolkata|Presidency College]], [[Calcutta]]. Fellow students included [[Nobel Memorial Prize in Economic Sciences]] winner [[Amartya Sen]] and member of [[Planning Commission (India)|planning commission]] [[Sukhamoy Chakravarty]] in 1953.<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/news/1999/sep/13/guardianobituaries3</ref>\n\n''Partha'' was a member of the [[Indian Council of Historical Research]]. He was Smuts Fellow in Commonwealth History at [[Cambridge University]] (1980-1981), and directeur d'\u00e9tudes at the Maison des Sciences de l'Homme in [[Paris]] in 1989.\n\n==Biography==\nPartho was born in 1934 in [[Guptipara]], Bengal of British India which is currently in [[Bangladesh]]. His father, Shaibal Kumar Gupta was in prestigious [[Indian Civil Services]] and mother [[Ashoka Gupta]] was a well known social worker who worked closely with [[Mahatma Gandhi]] during riots of Navakhali. He is the grandson of great Bengali writer of early 20th century [[Jyotirmoyee Devi]].\n\n===Early life===\n\nHe was a brilliant student and topped state matriculation examination in the year 1949. He then joined [[Presidency College, Kolkata|Presidency College]] Calcutta and graduated in history by getting highest marks and was given prestigious Eshan scholarship awarded for the highest marks in West Bengal. Fellow students that year included [[Amartya Sen]] and [[Sukhamoy Chakravarty]].<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/news/1999/sep/13/guardianobituaries3</ref> He went to [[England]] to continue his higher studies from [[The Queen's College, Oxford|Queen's College]], [[Oxford University]]. He graduated in modern history specialising in the [[English civil war]]. He worked closely with his teachers like [[Christopher Hill (historian)|Christopher Hill]] and [[Keith Thomas (historian)|Keith Thomas]]. He became friends with his batchmates [[Raphael Samuel]] and [[Peter Sedgwick]]. His British late-19th-century British railwaymen's union thesis earned him a Doctorate degree under the supervision of [[Henry Pelling]].\n\n===Teaching positions===\n\nGupta in the year 1960, joined [[Burdwan University]] in History Department briefly before joining [[Delhi University]] as a reader. He was teaching economic history before he became a reader in European and British history.\n\n===Marriage and children===\nHe married Narayani Gupta who taught history at [[Indraprastha College for Women]] and joined the [[Jamia Millia Islamia University]] in 1986. She was a consultant with [[Indian National Trust for Art and Cultural Heritage]].\nHer research has been on [[urban history]], particularly that of [[Delhi]]. She has many books to her credit. She was a founder member of the Conservation Society of Delhi and has been a member of the Delhi Urban Art Commission. She authored books Delhi between Empires 1803-1931, Society, Government and Urban Growth; Delhi Then & Now; and has co-authored Beato's Delhi: 1857 and Beyond. She has been an advisor for Delhi: The Built Heritage, A Listing, Intach, 2000.\n\nTogether they have a son Himadri Shikhar Gupta and a daughter Niharika Gupta.\n*Himadri Shikhar Gupta, alumnus of prestigious [[IIT Kanpur]] and [[Max Planck Institute of Colloids and Interfaces]] (MPIKG) at Potsdam (Germany) is teaching at  Institute of Bioengineering and School of Engineering and Materials Science, [[Queen Mary University]] of [[London]].<ref>https://www.sems.qmul.ac.uk/news/4743/the-gupta-group-visits-the-max-planck-institute-in-potsdam</ref><ref>https://samviti.com/profile/himadri-gupta-MTMy</ref>\n*Niharika Gupta is a [[Rhodes Scholar]] <ref>https://www.rhodeshouse.ox.ac.uk/alumni/rhodes-scholar-database/</ref> and alumnus of [[Delhi University]] and [[Balliol College]], [[University of Oxford]]. She is currently the Director of Research at [[Sahapedia]].<ref>https://www.sahapedia.org/sahapedia-team</ref>\n\n==Published works==\nImperialism And The British Labour Movement, 1914-1964<ref>https://g.co/kgs/6MK11G</ref><br/>\nTowards Freedom: Documents For The Movement For Independence In India, 1943-44<ref>https://www.indiatoday.in/magazine/society-the-arts/books/story/19971020-partha-sarathi-gupta-the-historians-research-took-him-back-to-his-roots-830745-1997-10-20</ref>\nPower, Politics and the People: Studies in British Imperialism and Indian Nationalism (New Delhi: Permanent Black, 2002)\nEdited, with Anirudh Deshpande. The British Raj and Its Indian Armed Forces, 1857-1939. New Delhi: Oxford University Press, 2002.\n\n==Honours, decorations, awards and distinctions==\nEshan scholarship awarded for the highest marks in [[West Bengal]]<br/>\nMember of the [[Indian Council of Historical Research]]<br/>\nSmuts Fellow in Commonwealth History at [[Cambridge University]]<br/>\nDirecteur d'\u00e9tudes at the Maison des Sciences de l'Homme in Paris<br/>\nFellow of the [[Royal Historical Society]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gupta, Partha Sarathi}}\n[[Category:1934 births]]\n[[Category:Indian academics]]\n[[Category:British historians]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian historians]]\n[[Category:Writers from Delhi]]\n[[Category:Historians of Europe]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Oxford]]\n[[Category:People from Delhi]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian writers]]\n[[Category:Historians of India]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian historians]]\n[[Category:Writers from West Bengal]]\n[[Category:Scholars from Delhi]]\n[[Category:Educators from West Bengal]]\n[[Category:Educators from Delhi]]\n[[Category:1999 deaths]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox academic\n| honorific_prefix   = Professor\n| name               = Partha Sarathi Gupta\n| honorific_suffix   = \n| image              = Partha sarathi Gupta.jpg\n| image_size         = \n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| native_name        = \n| native_name_lang   = \n| birth_name         = <!-- use only if different from full/othernames -->\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date |1934|08|05}}\n| birth_place        = \n| death_date         = {{Death date and age|1999|08|10|1934|08|05}}\n| death_place        = [[New Delhi]]\n| death_cause        = \n| region             = Delhi\n| nationality        = Indian\n| citizenship        = \n| residence          = New Delhi\n| other_names        = \n| occupation         = Professor of British and European History, [[Delhi University]]\n| period             = \n| known_for          = \n| home_town          = \n| title              = Ex-President, [[Indian History Congress]] \n| boards             = <!--board or similar positions extraneous to main occupation-->\n| spouse             = \n| partner            = \n| children           = \n| parents            =\n| relatives          =\n| awards             = [[Ishan Uday]]<br/> Smuts Fellow in Commonwealth History at [[Cambridge University]] (1980-1981)<br/> Fellow of the Royal Historical Society <br/>Editorial Advisory Board Member of the Journal of Imperial and Commonwealth History\n| website            = \n| education          = BA , MA, M Phil, PhD\n| alma_mater         = [[Presidency College, Calcutta]]<small>(BA)</small> <br/> [[Queen's College, Oxford]] <small>(MA, PhD)</small>\n| thesis_title       = \n| thesis_url         = \n| thesis_year        = 1956\n| school_tradition   = Liberalism\n| doctoral_advisor   = [[Henry Pelling]]\n| academic_advisors  = [[Christopher Hill (historian)|Christopher Hill]] <br/> [[Keith Thomas (historian)|Keith Thomas]]\n| influences         = \n| era                = 1914-1964\n| discipline         = [[Historian]]\n| sub_discipline     = Imperialism And The British [[Labour Movement]], Commonwealth History, [[English Civil War]] , Documents For The Movement For Independence In India, \n| workplaces         = \n| doctoral_students  = <!--only those with WP articles-->\n| notable_students   = \n| main_interests     = \n| notable_works      = Imperialism And The British Labour Movement, 1914-1964<br/> Towards Freedom: Documents For The Movement For Independence In India, 1943-44\n| notable_ideas      = \n| influenced         = <!--must be referenced from a third-party source-->\n| signature          = \n| signature_alt      = \n| signature_size     = \n| footnotes          = \n}}\n'''Partha Sarathi Gupta''' (5 August 1934 \u2013 10 August 1999) was an [[India]]n professor of British and European history at [[Delhi University]] and president of the [[Indian History Congress]]. He was firstborn son of [[Ashoka Gupta]] and Saibal Gupta, an [[Indian Civil Services]] officer in Bengal state of British India. His childhood memory of watching [[Mahatma Gandhi]]'s walk through riot-torn Noakhali in 1946 where his mother joined in the walk had a long-lasting impact. He was awarded Eshan scholarship for the highest marks in [[West Bengal]] in [[Presidency College, Kolkata|Presidency College]], [[Calcutta]]. Fellow students included [[Nobel Memorial Prize in Economic Sciences]] winner [[Amartya Sen]] and member of [[Planning Commission (India)|planning commission]] [[Sukhamoy Chakravarty]] in 1953.<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/news/1999/sep/13/guardianobituaries3</ref>\n\n''Partha'' was a member of the [[Indian Council of Historical Research]]. He was Smuts Fellow in Commonwealth History at [[Cambridge University]] (1980-1981), and directeur d'\u00e9tudes at the Maison des Sciences de l'Homme in [[Paris]] in 1989.\n\n==Biography==\nPartho was born in 1934 in [[Guptipara]], Bengal of British India which is currently in [[Bangladesh]]. His father, Shaibal Kumar Gupta was in prestigious [[Indian Civil Services]] and mother [[Ashoka Gupta]] was a well known social worker who worked closely with [[Mahatma Gandhi]] during riots of Navakhali. He is the grandson of great Bengali writer of early 20th century [[Jyotirmoyee Devi]]. \n\n===Early life===\n\nHe was a brilliant student and topped state matriculation examination in the year 1949. He then joined [[Presidency College, Kolkata|Presidency College]] Calcutta and graduated in history by getting highest marks and was given prestigious Eshan scholarship awarded for the highest marks in West Bengal. Fellow students that year included [[Amartya Sen]] and [[Sukhamoy Chakravarty]].<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/news/1999/sep/13/guardianobituaries3</ref> He went to [[England]] to continue his higher studies from [[The Queen's College, Oxford|Queen's College]], [[Oxford University]]. He graduated in modern history specialising in the [[English civil war]]. He worked closely with his teachers like [[Christopher Hill (historian)|Christopher Hill]] and [[Keith Thomas (historian)|Keith Thomas]]. He became friends with his batchmates [[Raphael Samuel]] and [[Peter Sedgwick]]. His British late-19th-century British railwaymen's union thesis earned him a Doctorate degree under the supervision of [[Henry Pelling]].\n\n===Teaching positions===\n\nGupta in the year 1960, joined [[Burdwan University]] in History Department briefly before joining [[Delhi University]] as a reader. He was teaching economic history before he became a reader in European and British history.\n\n===Marriage and children===\nHe married Narayani Gupta who taught history at [[Indraprastha College for Women]] and joined the [[Jamia Millia Islamia University]] in 1986. She was a consultant with [[Indian National Trust for Art and Cultural Heritage]].\nHer research has been on [[urban history]], particularly that of [[Delhi]]. She has many books to her credit. She was a founder member of the Conservation Society of Delhi and has been a member of the Delhi Urban Art Commission. She authored books Delhi between Empires 1803-1931, Society, Government and Urban Growth; Delhi Then & Now; and has co-authored Beato's Delhi: 1857 and Beyond. She has been an advisor for Delhi: The Built Heritage, A Listing, Intach, 2000.\n\nTogether they have a son Himadri Shikhar Gupta and a daughter Niharika Gupta.\n*Himadri Shikhar Gupta, alumnus of prestigious [[IIT Kanpur]] and [[Max Planck Institute of Colloids and Interfaces]] (MPIKG) at Potsdam (Germany) is teaching at  Institute of Bioengineering and School of Engineering and Materials Science, [[Queen Mary University]] of [[London]].<ref>https://www.sems.qmul.ac.uk/news/4743/the-gupta-group-visits-the-max-planck-institute-in-potsdam</ref><ref>https://samviti.com/profile/himadri-gupta-MTMy</ref>\n\n*Niharika Gupta is a [[Rhodes Scholar]] <ref>https://www.rhodeshouse.ox.ac.uk/alumni/rhodes-scholar-database/</ref> and alumnus of [[Delhi University]] and [[Balliol College]], [[University of Oxford]]. She is currently the Director of Research at [[Sahapedia]].<ref>https://www.sahapedia.org/sahapedia-team</ref>\n\n==Published works==\nImperialism And The British Labour Movement, 1914-1964<ref>https://g.co/kgs/6MK11G</ref><br/>\nTowards Freedom: Documents For The Movement For Independence In India, 1943-44<ref>https://www.indiatoday.in/magazine/society-the-arts/books/story/19971020-partha-sarathi-gupta-the-historians-research-took-him-back-to-his-roots-830745-1997-10-20</ref>\nPower, Politics and the People: Studies in British Imperialism and Indian Nationalism (New Delhi: Permanent Black, 2002)\nEdited, with Anirudh Deshpande. The British Raj and Its Indian Armed Forces, 1857-1939. New Delhi: Oxford University Press, 2002.\n\n==Honours, decorations, awards and distinctions==\nEshan scholarship awarded for the highest marks in [[West Bengal]]<br/>\nMember of the [[Indian Council of Historical Research]]<br/>\nSmuts Fellow in Commonwealth History at [[Cambridge University]]<br/>\nDirecteur d'\u00e9tudes at the Maison des Sciences de l'Homme in Paris<br/>\nFellow of the [[Royal Historical Society]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gupta, Partha Sarathi}}\n[[Category:1934 births]]\n[[Category:Indian academics]]\n[[Category:British historians]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian historians]]\n[[Category:Writers from Delhi]]\n[[Category:Historians of Europe]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Oxford]]\n[[Category:People from Delhi]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian writers]]\n[[Category:Historians of India]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian historians]]\n[[Category:Writers from West Bengal]]\n[[Category:Scholars from Delhi]]\n[[Category:Educators from West Bengal]]\n[[Category:Educators from Delhi]]\n[[Category:1999 deaths]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "commen